The maintenance tunnel entrance was exactly where I left it. Rusted metal hatch unlocked. I texted Vega, kill your radios, count to 30, then move to northwest corner inside, near the old freight elevator. I'll get you out. No reply. Just 8 11 50. Eight p m, I crawled through the tunnel, came up inside the building through a floor grate in the electrical room. At exactly 0:00 12, I cut the main breaker. Total darkness. Chaos erupted, shouting confusion. Vega and his team moved exactly where I told them. I covered from the shadows, directed them through the tunnel. No shots fired from my end. Didn't need To all six officers out in four minutes. Morrison showed up ten minutes later. Tactical vest, radio. Trying to look in charge. Saw me standing by my car. Walked over, extended his hand. Garrett, thank god you saved. I looked at his hand. Didn't move. Send the invoice to the city. My consulting rate is $5,000 an hour. His face dropped. Garrett, come on. Don't be like that. You said I wasn't police anymore. So treat me like a contractor. I just worked three hours. That's $15,000. That's insane. So is calling a guy you fired and expecting free labor. I got in my car. Invoice arrives Monday. Morrison tried blocking payment. Called it unreasonable rates for civilian assistance. I sent the city attorney my recordings. Every call, every text. Morrison's personal request, Vega's Mayday. The check cleared two weeks later. $15,000. Morrison got demoted, laterally transferred to some desk job in records. Vega called. You really charge them every cent? He laughed. Respect. Last month, I got a text from the new chief. We're hiring. Interested? I replied. My rate just doubled. They paid it. I start Monday.

They were hunched over Freddy's phone, heads touching. When Freddy spotted me through the window, he shoved the phone in his pocket. Lola stood up so fast she knocked over her coffee. Wednesday, she went to a medical building and sat in the parking lot for two hours, just sitting there, staring at the entrance. He texted he'd be home late from his client's dinner. But then I saw him leave the building and get in her car. Thursday night, while Freddy slept, I went through everything, his phone, his laptop, his car, found nothing about an affair. She's always been jealous of what we have. Single, desperate. He took my hand. Whatever she's telling you, she's trying to break us apart. You can't go to Switzerland. Don't let her ruin us. Freddy has ALS, early onset genetic. My heart broke. Why didn't he tell me, I whispered. His mother nodded. At family dinner last week when you were at work, he said, she stopped, tears falling. Lola showed me text between Freddy and his mother. Smart women make the best caretakers. They give up everything out of guilt. You knew, Lola. My voice cracked. He told us you were too emotional to handle it, but last night he said you'd be pregnant within three months. Once you had his baby, you'd never abandon a sick husband. She grabbed my hands. He called you his retirement plan, free nursing for life. Lola opened her laptop. I called Switzerland. They extended your deadline for another 24 hours. I packed my bags and hired a divorce lawyer.

I'm really clumsy. Mrs. Haskins put down her pen and looked at me with the saddest eyes I've ever seen. Honey, we both know that's not true. My heart started racing. It is true. I swear. The bell rang and kids started packing up. I grabbed my backpack and headed for the door, but Mrs. Haskins called my name. Can you wait a few minutes before you go to the bus? This, it was bad. This was really bad. Missus Haskins closed the door. Once the classroom was empty, I stood there, backpack on, ready to run. What's happening? I asked. Am I in trouble? Missus Haskins shook her head. You're not in trouble, sweetheart, but I need you to stay here for just a few more minutes. Through the classroom window, I watched Mom's car pull into the parent pickup lane. She got out looking annoyed, probably wondering why I wasn't in the car already. Then the front office secretary stepped outside and met her at the entrance. Mom's face changed to confusion. The secretary was talking, gesturing toward the building. Then Principal Morton came out. Then two police officers appeared from inside the building. My stomach dropped. Oh, no. Oh, no. Oh, no. Oh, no. Mom's confusion turned to rage in seconds. Mouth was moving fast, yelling one Of the officers stepped toward her and said something. Mom jerked backward and screamed loud enough that I could hear it through the glass. Get away from me. This is insane. My son is fine. The second officer moved closer. Mom spun between them, pointing at the building, at her car, her hands flying everywhere. He's a liar. He makes things up for attention. That boy is dramatic. The first officer pulled out handcuffs. Mom's eyes went huge. This is harassment, police brutality. My son fell off his bike. He's clumsy. You can't arrest me for this. They clicked the cuffs around her wrists. Mom thrashed, her face purple with rage. I'm his mother. I feed him. I clothe him. I do everything for that ungrateful brat. How dare you do this to me. He twisted around, scanning the windows frantically. When her eyes found mine, she screamed, this is your fault. You ruined everything. I told you what would happen. The officers guided her toward the patrol car while she kept screaming, fighting, her voice cracking as they put her in the back seat. I couldn't stop my body from shaking. One of the officers came inside and knelt in front of me. You're safe now, he said. But I didn't feel safe.

Suggested I consider online school for everyone's comfort. My parents were mortified. Mom cried every night. Dad wouldn't look at me. Even if you were sick. Principals at other schools literally said they couldn't accommodate a student with my reputation. I started doubting myself. What if I blacked out so hard I didn't remember? I was going insane. But then it hit me. If it genuinely wasn't me, some one had to have framed me. Someone staged this whole thing and destroyed my life. But who? After three more months of torture, my parents moved us two states away. I finished senior year at a school where I was just the new girl. Graduated quietly, went to college where nobody knew me. Five years passed. I rebuild everything. New city, new friends, good job. Even started dating someone amazing who believed my story. I'd honestly stopped caring who it was that did that to me. My life was better without any of them. I found a good job in marketing, made real friends who actually trusted me. When I told them about the whole Chiron party nightmare, they all just held me while I cried. That's horrific, they said. I can't believe they did that to you. Last week, everything changed. The doorbell rang. I opened it to find Aisha standing there. She looked older, tired. Hey, she said quietly, I know you probably hate me, but I started to close the door. I don't care anymore. Aisha, please, she said, putting her foot in the door. I know the truth now about Chiron's party. You need to hear this. I started closing the door, but Aisha pushed past me. It was Maggie. She did everything. My chest tightened. My friend since elementary school. Maggie. She hired that girl, found her on Craigslist, coached her through everything. Maggie knew Karen was going to ask you to prom. He'd been working up the courage for months. My heart stopped beating. She thought if you were humiliated enough, Karen would be too disgusted to ever think about you again. But it backfired. Never dated anyone after that and was too traumatized by what happened at his house. How do you know this? Tears formed in her eyes. She confessed at a college party last month. Drunk, crying. Said she's been in therapy about it. Five years of my life were destroyed because Maggie was jealous of Chiron wanting me. Everyone knows. Now they want to apologize. I shut the door in her face.

My unemployed sister tried to give me career advice and I embarrassed her in front of our family. I just earned my PhD from a prestigious university outside my country. It took six years of sleepless nights and fighting through a learning disability. There were nights I'd sit at my desk until 3:00am unable to process a single paragraph. I'd call my dad crying, saying I couldn't do it. He'd stay on the phone for hours telling me to take it one page at a time. But I made it. When I came home, dad threw a huge Celebration dinner. He invited aunts, uncles, cousins, everyone. He was so proud he couldn't stop smiling. I was excited to share what I'd accomplished. Then there's my sister, Jane. She's 36, unemployed and has lived with our parents for eight years. She needs to be the center of every conversation. She gives unsolicited advice, constantly interrupting people to share her wisdom on topics she knows nothing about. My mom always defends her. Jane is incredibly talented. She just needs room to achieve her potential. Dad and I tried reasoning with mom for years, but she's stubborn. In our culture, you play nice with family no matter how insufferable they are. The dinner started fine. Relatives were congratulating me, asking about my research. Then James started her routine. She kept cutting me off. She'd launch into elaborate stories about job offers from Google or plans to travel Europe, pursuing music and art. None. Of it was true. She hasn't worked in almost a decade. Every time someone showed genuine interest in my work, she'd interrupt with another tall tale about her own success. Then came the moment that changed every everything. My mom cornered me in the dining room. Jane wants to give you advice. It's important. She's guiding you as a good older sister should. Dad immediately stood next to me. He knew this was bad. Jane started going on about what she did after high school to become unsuccessful. The irony was suffocating. Mom and several relatives were knotting along like she was delivering profound wisdom. Dad and my younger cousins looked completely done. I zoned out, not wanting to engage. That's when she noticed. She snapped her fingers right in front of my eyes, annoyed. I'm giving you such good advice here. You should pay attention so you can do well like me. Something in me snapped. Instead of apologizing like I've done for years, I looked her straight in the.

Had apparently attacked him without warning, striking him with something hard enough to fracture his skull and cause a concussion. She pulled out her phone and showed me a photo of Connor in a hospital bed, his head wrapped in bandages, his face swollen beyond recognition. But something didn't make sense. Though he weighed maybe 55 pounds and had never shown any signs of aggression, I asked if I could see my daughter first before we discussed anything else. Principal Hartwell nodded, leading me down the hallway, while Officer Valdez followed at a respectful distance. Missus Blackwood stayed behind, but I could feel her hatred boring into my back. The counselor's office smelled like vanilla and old books. Zoe sat in an oversized chair with her legs drawn up to her chest, looking impossibly small. Her right knuckles were scraped raw, dried blood visible in the creases of her small fingers. When she looked up at me, I saw something in her eyes I'd never seen before, not fear or guilt, but a kind of cold determination that made her look older than her eight years. The school counselor, Miss Rivera, pulled me aside and whispered that Zoe had refused to explain what happened, just kept asking if Sammy was okay. I had no idea who Sammy was or why Zoe would be more concerned about some other child than the fact that she was about to be arrested. I sat down next to my daughter and took her uninjured. Hand asking her as calmly as I could manage to tell me what happened. She looked at me with those suddenly ancient eyes and said five words that changed everything. Connor was hurting little Sammy. Dad. My breath caught in my throat. Sammy Fletcher was a five year old with autism who attended the school's special needs program. He was nonverbal and had severe sensory processing issues that made him vulnerable to over stimulation and meltdowns. We explained in her small voice that she'd been reading under the big oak tree when she heard crying coming from behind the maintenance shed. When she went to investigate, she found Connor and two of his friends surrounding Sammy who was on the ground rocking back and forth and making the distressed sounds he made when overwhelmed. Connor was filming with his phone while his friends threw pebbles at Sammy and laughed. I felt rage flash through me so intense had to grip the chair arms to stay grounded. Zoe described how she told them to stop but Connor had just laughed and said something about getting content for his social media. He then deliberately poured his chocolate milk over Sammy's head while still filming, causing the little boy to have a complete meltdown. Sammy had started hitting himself in the head, which only made the teenagers laugh harder. That's when Zoe had apparently picked up a rock from the ground and thrown it as hard as she could at Connor's head. Full Story on my channel and linked below.

I paid my parents $700 a week, but they didn't come to my child's birthday party. I asked why, and my dad replied, your child doesn't exist for us. I didn't say anything. Trembling, I cut them off. Forty minutes later, Karma caught up with them. My daughter kept asking when Nana and Grandpa were coming. I was lighting the candles on her sixth birthday cake, watching her twirl in her sparkly pink dress. Every few minutes, she'd run to the gate looking down the empty street. Soon, baby, I said. But I already knew they weren't coming. The backyard was full of kids and noise, wrapping paper, balloons, frosting on fingers. Her friends screamed in the bounce house and my daughter, my hopeful, forgiving daughter, kept watching that gate. They never showed that night. After I washed icing out of her hair, I sat on the couch and stared at my phone. One text, tell Ava happy birthday from us. That was it. No call, no visit. I sent them $700 that Monday, like every Monday for eight months, rent, groceries, bills, excuses. I called. My dad answered, why didn't you come? Silence. Then he said, your child doesn't exist for us. He hung up. I stared at the phone. Then I opened my banking app and cancelled every payment, every single one. 40 minutes later, a text, can you order us dinner? Nothing fancy. There's no food in the house. I turned off my phone and went to Bed. By Wednesday, their landlord called, said rent hadn't come through, called me reliable. That word stung. I told him I wouldn't be paying anymore. That night, my mom texted again. So you're really leaving us with nothing. I blocked her number. The next morning, I called my brother Ryan, told him everything. He went quiet, then said, I've been sending them money, too. I froze. What? Groceries, phone bills. I thought maybe they'd come around. Maybe they'd love Ava, he sighed. But they never will, will they? No, I said, they won't. He paused. Then, I'm done, too. The next day, my mom called from a new number screaming Ryan had cut them off, told them he was finished. She said I'd poisoned him, that I'd ruined the family. I hung up. But Ryan didn't stop there.

You'd think I'd risen from the dead. I sat at the adult table, filled my plate with hot, fresh food. No leftovers, no picked over scraps. Sarah snapped, looks like someone's gotten too big for their boots at college. Forgotten all about sisterly duties. I took my time chewing. Funny thing about sisterly duties, I don't remember free babysitter being in the manual. Maybe you could show me the chapter where parents don't watch their own kids. Gasps around the table. Aunt Janet literally clutched her pearls. The next morning they ambushed me. Mom, Dad, Sarah, Emma, sitting in formation. What kind of performance was that yesterday, Sarah hissed, making us look like bad parents in front of everyone. I'm just tired of being the unpaid, unappreciated babysitter while everyone else gets an actual holiday. They all started talking at once. Guilt trips, lectures, reminders of everything they've done for me. Then Sarah played her Trump card. Maybe it's time someone taught you a lesson about gratitude. Let's see how you manage without mom and dad paying your college tuition. The room went silent. Smiled. Actually, Sarah, Grandma's been paying my tuition from Grandpa's education fund, you know, the same one that put you through nursing school. And even if that wasn't true, I have a scholarship. Unlike some people, I'm not afraid of working to support myself. I walked upstairs, packed in 10 minutes and left. As I drove back to campus, I blocked all their numbers. Mom, Dad, Sarah, Emma, each tap felt like breaking another link in a chain. Two months later, they showed up at my dorm. Mom, dad and Emma. No, Sarah, can we buy you coffee? Emma asked. I'd like to talk at the campus cafe. Mom spoke first. After you left, we had some very long conversations. Ruby, we were wrong. We took advantage of you for years and called it family duty. Dad cleared his throat. You deserved your own holidays, your own life. What about Sarah? I asked Emma Side. She's still processing. You know how she is. I studied their faces. Sincerity, regret. Okay. I said, I believe you. I unblocked their numbers. Things are different now. Emma watches her own kids. Mom stopped orchestrating bonding moments that ended with me in charge. Sarah and I still haven't spoken. Sometimes I see her posts, her boys growing up fast. Part of me hopes she'll realize what she did wrong, that she'll reach out first. Until then, I'm at peace with the distance.

My parents think my sister deserves my inherited apartment because she's the better child. My parents have always favored Jessica. But what happened after my grandmother died crossed every line. Grandma left me her downtown apartment, nothing fancy, worth about $180,000. Jessica makes six figures, drives a BMW, lives in a luxury condo with her surgeon boyfriend. I'm a graphic designer making decent money, but I've been renting for years. Two weeks after the funeral, my parents sat me down. We think Jessica should have the apartment. She's more successful. She'd make better use of it. They wanted me to sign it over for the good of the family. I said no, the apartment was left to me. If grandma wanted Jessica to have it, she would have left it to Jessica. My mom said, this is exactly why you'll never amount to anything, David. You're selfish and small minded. My dad added, look at your sister. She's successful. She's engaged to a doctor. What do you have to show for your life? They gave me one week to reconsider. Two weeks later, I went to the apartment to sort grandma's belongings. Jessica was inside with a measuring tape. Oh, David, perfect timing. I'm getting measurements for the renovation. We're thinking of knocking out this wall. My mom had given her a key. Jessica, I'm not signing over the apartment. She looked genuinely confused. Be reasonable. You can't afford to renovate properly. Michael and I have the vision and resources. Grandma was old. She didn't understand real estate potential. I changed the locks the next day. A week later, Jessica showed up with Michael. He had spreadsheets, renovation plans, neighborhood projections. We're offering you 50 thousand dollars for the apartment. That's free money, David. You could never afford the 80 thousand dollar renovation we're planning. I told them no. Jessica's tone shifted. David, let's be honest. You're 28, single, living in a studio. Your income is inconsistent. This apartment is probably the most valuable thing you'll ever own. Then she said it. Grandmother gave it to you out of pity. She felt sorry for you because you never got your life together like I did. Last week, my parents showed up at my workplace. They brought a lawyer, transfer documents, a notary stamp. Jessica gets the apartment. You get $100,000 cash. Everyone wins. My boss let us use his office. My dad spread the papers on his desk.

Jessica has earned the right to have nice things. I looked at them standing in my boss's office, trying to humiliate me into compliance. When was the last time you asked about my work without comparing it to Jessica's job? Your work? My dad laughed. You make websites for restaurants. Jessica developed strategies for Fortune 500 companies. There's no comparison. Exactly. There's no comparison. Because you don't value what I do. My boss finally spoke. David is one of our most talented designers. His salary is his business, but he's valued here. My parents looked shocked. Three days ago, they showed up at the apartment with Jessica, Michael, and their lawyer. My dad pushed past me. We're done playing games. They had a final offer. $100,000 cash. Jessica was holding renovation catalogs. Look what we could do with this space. Michael added. We've already put down deposits with contractors. I looked at Jessica, avoiding eye contact. Jessica, do you remember what grandma said about this apartment? David, she said a lot of things. She said it was her sanctuary, the one place that was completely hers. And she left it to me because she understood what it felt like to be the overlooked one. My dad exploded. You weren't overlooked. You were disappointing. Dad, when was the last time you asked about my life without comparing it to Jessica's? Silence. I want all of you to leave. No. My dad stepped forward. You sign those papers, or. Or what? You'll Disown me. You already have. My mom was crying. David, you're tearing this family apart over money. No, you tore this family apart the moment you decided Jessica deserved my inheritance more than I did. They filed out. Jessica turned at the door. I'm sorry it came to this. I'm sorry it took 28 years to realize how you all really see me. I've been living in grandma's apartment for a week now. Painting the walls, colors she would have liked, making it mine while honoring who she was. The apartment feels like home in a way nowhere else ever have. As my parents were wrong about one thing. I do have something to show for my life. Self respect, boundaries. And a beautiful apartment. My grandmother left me because she loved me and believed I deserved it. That's more than enough.

That's my company. Dad leaned forward. Don't be ridiculous. The buyers were from out of state. Spencer is my middle name. Used it for the LLC legal. Clean, quiet. Jenna's face turned red. Why would you do that behind our backs? It was for sale. I made an offer. We would have gotten so much more if we knew it was you, mom blurted there. It was not about legacy, not about grandma, about money. Funny, I replied. I got it below. Asking your realtor wasn't great. The rest of dinner was tense silence. Jenna stabbed at her food. You mean you and dad make decisions? Jenna cheers. Tyler coasts, go along. That's not fair. What's not fair is telling me I wasn't in Grandma's will. Like I didn't matter to her. She flinched. While they spun damage control, I quietly dug into Grandma's actual will. But I found changed everything. Real will dated a month before she died, left the house to me, to my beloved grandson, Noah, who has always valued the history and heart of our family. They'd hidden it, filed an older version, forged documents and Filed the wrong will. I hired a lawyer. We sued for fraud. The evidence was overwhelming. Forged signatures, hidden trusts, covered paperwork. Six months later, we won everything. Court ruled the house rightfully mine, awarded damages and my parents paid restitution plus legal fees. Best part, I turned Grandma's house into a community center. Newspaper ran grandson honors grandmother's legacy. Despite family betrayal. Family reputation crumbled overnight. Mom resigned from community council. Jenna's wedding business lost clients. Dad's deals fell through. Tyler texted, didn't know everything but should have. Sorry I didn't reply. It wasn't about apologies. It was about what they did when they thought I couldn't fight back. Today, Grandma's house host book clubs, memory nights. Her legacy lives no longer trapped by lies. Outside the sheets for once. Lowell, the guy responded with a shirtless mirror pic. I recognized the bathroom, the birchstone again. That hotel always smelled like cheap lavender. The guy, a contractor we hired last summer to fix our deck. I gave him beer. He thanked me, shook my hand. I kept digging. Her car's GPS tracking three separate Tuesday visits to a downtown condo. She always told me she hated downtown. Printed everything, organized it by date. Her messages to him were sweet, flirty, nothing like how she talked to me. One text made my blood run cold. He's nice but dull. A placeholder. My life started late. Placeholder. That night around midnight, Jennifer fell asleep watching some podcast. I went back to my office and pulled out a small wooden box I'd made myself, originally meant to hold flinks. I filled it with a flash drive containing every screenshot, every email, every G P s coordinate. I added a printed map with her affair location circled in red. One blurry photo of her and him. Her special necklace visible, the one she only wore for important occasions. Then I wrote a note by hand. Three days to pack, then I file or we pretend none of this happened. Your choice. I placed the box on her pillow and went to bed. When she found it the next morning, she didn't scream. She just stared for an hour. Finally, she opened it and I watched her face in the Hallway mirror. She read the note over and over, hands shaking, phone buzzed. She didn't even look at it. She didn't sleep that night or the next, or the next. Day one, she brought me roses, made soup from scratch, wore lingerie, tried everything. I just said you should rest. Day 2, she wanted to talk, suggested couples therapy of vacation. Then she called her lawyer and I heard her scream through the bathroom door, you never mentioned a fidelity clause. Turns out our prenup had one with proof. Everything changes. Day 3, she got quiet, really quiet. Just walked around touching things like she was saying goodbye. That evening, I came home to find her suitcases packed. She asked me one question, do you hate me? I said, no, I just finally love myself enough not to be quiet anymore. She left. That night, I locked the door, turned off my phone and slept better than I had in years. Sometimes the quietest revenge is just refusing to be a placeholder anymore.

My boyfriend argued with everything I said until I agreed with him about breaking up. So my boyfriend, Jake, literally cannot let me finish a single sentence without correcting me, arguing with me or explaining why I'm wrong. And yesterday I finally turned it around on him. This man would argue with me if I said the sky was blue, he'd say, actually it's more of a cyan and launch into a lecture about light wavelengths. I'd say I'm hungry. He'd say, no, you're not. You just ate three hours ago. You're probably just thirsty. I'd say I liked a movie. He'd explain why it was actually terrible and I just didn't understand cinema. Every opinion, every feeling, every thought I had was apparently wrong and needed his correction. The most annoying part was he'd phrase it like he was helping me be smarter. He'd start with actually or, well, technically or let me explain why that's not quite right. Like I was a toddler who needed basic concepts explained. Once said my head hurt and he goes, it's probably not a headache. You're likely experiencing tension from poor posture. Like he was inside my skull feeling what I felt. He argued about the dumbest things, too. I said I saw 12 birds on the wire outside and he made me go back and count them to prove they were only 11. I said the restaurant was about five minutes away and he pulled up Google Maps to show it was Actually seven minutes. Said my mom called me twice and he checked my phone log to point out she called three times but I missed one. It was exhausting. I started not talking just to avoid the corrections. But even silence wasn't safe because then he'd argue about why I was quiet, saying I was being passive aggressive or Moody. Really, I just didn't want to hear another lecture about why my thoughts were wrong. Last week I tested him and said something completely factual, that the capital of France is Paris. And he goes, well, actually it depends on what you mean by capital because historically there were different administrative regions. And went on for 10 minutes. He couldn't even let me have Paris. The breaking point was building for weeks. Every time he corrected me, I'd just say, okay, but I was keeping track. 73 corrections in one week, 73 times he felt the need to explain why I was wrong about something, including my own feelings and experiences. I started writing them all down in my phone with time stamps and everything. Then yesterday we're at his friend's birthday party and I'm telling a story about my coworker. I said she was about 30 years old. And Jake immediately goes, actually she's 32. I looked her up on LinkedIn in front of everyone. His friend Tom goes, dude, why do you know her exact age? That's weird. And Jake starts arguing with Tom about how it's not Weird. To be accurate, I saw my opening and said, you know what, Jake, you're absolutely right about everything. You're right that I'm too emotional. You're right that I don't understand movies. You're.

Videos of my daughter's first time on Small World, her first dole whip, her first time meeting a Disney princess, all moments I missed while working to support the family. The comments underneath killed me. Best day ever with my favourite little princess and this little one stole my heart and can't wait for our next adventure. Our next adventure. Like they were a family unit. Like I was just the person paying bills. Three days before his mother's birthday, I still haven't planned anything. Anthony kept asking about the party. I told him it was handled day before. He panicked and asked for details so he could tell his family. I gave him an address and a time, 2:00 Saturday at Riverside Park Pavilion. He asked about food and I said it was covered. Morning of the party, he dressed up nice and put Rosie in her fancy dress, the one Britney bought her at Disneyland. We drove to the park in silence. When we arrived, there was nothing. No decorations, no food, no guests because I hadn't invited anyone. Just an empty Pavilion with picnic tables. Anthony stood there looking around while Rosie played in the dirt. His phone started ringing. His mother asking where everyone was. His siblings wondering if they had the wrong location. Turn to me with his face red. There's no party, he said, like he was just figuring it out. That's right. I said I didn't plan anything. He asked how I could Do this to his mother the same way you took our daughter to Disneyland without me. I said, Brittany can plan the party. She seems to have plenty of free time and energy. Family started arriving confused and angry. His mother called me trashy and classless, said this was why Anthony needed better influences in his life. I took Rosie and left them all standing in that empty Pavilion. I filed for divorce the next Monday. He was shocked, said I was overreacting to one trip and one party. But it wasn't one anything. It was a pattern of choosing everyone except the person funding his life.

She missed every doctor's appointment, every late night homework session. My lawyer told me my involvement made a strong case for primary custody. Six weeks in, she noticed. She tried to spark conversations. I answered in single words. She tried dressing up to get a rise too late. One night, she sat on the couch beside me. You've lost weight. You look good. Thanks. Can we talk? There's a wall between us. I'm respecting the parameters you set, I said. You were very clear about what I am to you. She tried to explain, but I asked the one question she couldn't answer. When you said I'm nothing more than a co parent, what did you expect me to do? She had no answer. The final confirmation came when I overheard her on the phone. He's completely different. Not angry, just gone. I didn't really want a divorce. I just wanted him to pay attention to me. Her bluntness revealed the manipulation. She'd hoped a threat to our marriage would make me change. Instead, I called her bluff. Three months later, I sat at the kitchen table with a Manila folder. I want a divorce, I said. Silence. I slid the folder across signed paperwork and statements and the documentation of every school event I'd covered while she was away. My lawyer's letter explained that given my role and income, primary custody was likely. She would be expected to contribute child support. Her face went white. Courts always favor the Mother, she said, not when the record shows who was actually present, I replied. The judge awarded me primary custody. Sarah kept every other weekend and one dinner per week. The look on her face was shocked. The house sold. I bought a smaller, nicer place near the kids school. Sarah moved into a one bedroom and took an entry level admin role that barely covered rent. Two years later, she still calls, sometimes after a bad date, crying about mistakes. I don't fuel that. I answer when I need to. I keep my focus on the twins. I've rebuilt a life that centers on them. I'm not interested in revenge. I'm focused on stability and on giving Ethan and Elsa the dependable home they deserve. I blocked her number for long stretches. I cleared my messages. I packed for a new start because protecting my kids mattered more than punishing anyone.

The problem was what the officer said next. She also claims you threatened her, refused to help and told her she'd regret it. My hands clenched. That's a complete lie. Then you won't mind coming to the station. At the station, they showed me Jessica's statement. Pure fiction. She claimed I've been drinking, that I crashed, that I abandoned her. And at the bottom, witnesses David and Linda Carter, parents confirming Jessica's story. My own parents had signed a statement. Again, hence me. I leaned back, voice deadly calm. Officer, I'd like to file my own report. He raised an eyebrow. Jessica Carter stole my vehicle. I never gave permission. I want to press charges for grand theft auto. The tables turned instantly. Within three hours, Jessica's employer called. We're conducting an internal review. Your sister listed you as a character witness. I told them everything. They thanked me and hung up. Jessica called 14 times that day. I ignored everyone. Then the voicemail. They fired me. Do you hear me? They fired me. I hope you're happy. I didn't bother listening to the rest. My parents showed up that night. You need to fix this. She lost everything because of you. I shook my head. Because of me or because she lied to the police? Mom's eyes narrowed. She's your sister. If you don't take her in, she'll be homeless. I looked them both in the eyes. No. Mom gasped like I'd slapped her. You took her side. You. Called me selfish. You backed her lies, and now you want me to open my home to her. We're family, Michael. Family forgives. I exhaled slowly. Not this time. And I shut the door. Three days later, Jessica showed up, hair a mess, clothes wrinkled, eyes death desperate. Michael, I have nowhere to go. I stared at her, years of resentment boiling beneath my skin. You tried to get me arrested, Jess. I know, she whispered. I just, I need my brother back. For a split second, she looked like my little sister again. But I knew this was the moment I had to choose. You need me when it's convenient. You took my car, lied to the police, and now you expect me to forgive you. Her lips trembled. Michael, please, goodbye, Jess. And for the last time, I shut the door. Two months later, I moved. New city, new job, new life. No calls, no messages. And for the first time, I was living for me.

My husband took our daughter to Disneyland with his best friend and let her play mom in every photo. That's when the switch flipped. My husband took our two year old daughter to Disneyland without me because his best friend Brittany had free tickets that expired that weekend. I was working a 12 hour shift at the hospital and couldn't get coverage. He said they couldn't waste the tickets and promised to take photos. Our daughter's first time seeing Mickey Mouse and I watched it through text messages while drawing blood from patients. Brittany was in every single photo holding my daughter's hand, carrying her on her shoulders, hugging her in front of the castle. My husband barely appeared in any of them. I've been planning that Disneyland trip for months. Had a savings jar labeled Rosie's first Disney trip where I put extra money from overtime shifts, bought her a special Minnie Mouse dress she was supposed to wear, made a list of all the rides appropriate for toddlers, researched the best times to avoid crowds, even Learned where all the character meet and greet happened. But Anthony and Britney just went without any planning because free tickets don't wait. He came home that night with Rosie passed out in her car seat, chocolate on her face, wearing a new princess dress I didn't buy Brit. He had bought it for her. Inside the park said every little girl need a princess dress for Disney. Anthony thought that was Sweet. I thought about how I'd worked three extra shifts to save for that exact dress in a bigger size for when we went as a family. Britney started coming around more after that. She'd drop by during dinner because she was in the neighborhood, always brought Rosie little gifts, stickers or candy or cheap toys from the dollar store. My daughter started calling her Auntie Britt. Anthony said it was good for Rosie to have positive female influences beyond just mom. I asked what was wrong with my influence? I was always tired from work and Britney had more energy for playing. She didn't have more energy. She just didn't work 12 hour nursing shifts to pay for our mortgage while he pursued his music career that brought in maybe $200 a month from guitar lessons. Last month, Anthony informed me his mother's 70th birthday was coming up and we needed to plan something special. By we, he meant me. He wanted a full party with catering, decorations, a photo booth, a whole production that I was so good at organizing things and his mom deserved the best. His mom, who hadn't visited once since Rosie was born, who forgot my birthday every year but remembered Britney's, who asked why Anthony settled for someone who worked such long hours instead of being home. I told him I'd think about it. He'd already told his family I was handling everything. His sister called the next day asking about The menu. His brother wanted to know the menu. His mother called to say she hoped I wouldn't embarrass the family with something cheap. Meanwhile, Brittany posted photos from Disneyland every day that week, pictures I hadn't seen.

My parents gave my sister a luxury villa and left me an empty parking lot. You can always sleep under the stars, they snickered. But when I turned it into a business, they wanted to share. I should have known this dinner was a setup. My parents never invited me over unless they needed something, usually to remind me I was the family disappointment. My sister, Emily, their golden child, never worked a day but somehow deserved everything. Dad folded his newspaper. We're dividing our assets. Emily lit up instantly. Mom smiled. We're giving you the beach house, sweetheart. Emily gasped like she'd won an Oscar, the one in Malibu. Then dad turned to me, expression flat. And you, Logan, we're giving you the parking lot. Silence. The what? The old lot on 8th Street, mom said, waving dismissively. It's land. Figure something out. Emily burst out laughing. At least you'll always have a place to sleep under the stars, dad chuckled. Maybe open a lemonade stand or something. I stared at them. This wasn't even disguised kindness. This, it was straight garbage. A memory flashed me at 16, holding my first paycheck from the auto shop. So proud, dad didn't even look up. You're going to smell like oil for the rest of your life. That same week, they bought Emily a brand new BMW. I pushed back from the table. You're serious, dad shrugged. You should be grateful, I stood. I'll make something of it. Emily rolled her Eyes can't wait to see what you do with a slab of concrete. Three weeks later, I had permits for food trucks. I took out a loan from my boss, a guy who actually believed in hard work, and set up lights, seating, banners. That worthless parking lot became a full blown food court with live music and lines around the block. One month in, mom showed up in her expensive coat, wrinkling her nose at the crowd. So this is what you've done? I didn't look at her. You gave me trash. I made it work. This isn't a real business, she sniffed. It's just a fate.

My wife blindsided me for her boss and kicked me out. So I got revenge doing exactly what the judge told me to do. I came home one day to find my stuff being packed, boxes everywhere. My wife of eight years handed me a Protection order. I couldn't come home without written permission for 90 days. I had to email her just to see my own kids. I was completely blindsided. A relative connected me with this bulldog lawyer. She was brilliant and told me these orders take time to fight. We probably wouldn't see a judge before the 90 days were up. But she was crystal clear about one thing, follow the court order to the letter. Any violation and I'd be screwed if my ex tried to renew it. It took exactly one day before my ex needed me. She called asking me to watch the kids. I had crashed at a friend's house so I had nowhere to take them. We agreed I'd watch them at home. I parked three blocks away and waited for the email. She called annoyed. I reminded her about the order. No written permission, no entry. She finally sent it. This happened two more times that first week. Each time I sat in my car down the street waiting for an email while my kids were inside. So I told her moving forward, I wouldn't leave my temporary place until I had permission. That was 20 minutes away. She agreed. Then Immediately forgot. The next morning, we'd planned for me to pick up the kids and take them to school. Their school was five minutes from my work, so it made sense. I waited at my friend's place. No email came. Time kept ticking. I calculated the drive. If I left right then, I could barely make it to the house, get the kids, drop them at school and still make it to work on time. But I didn't have written permission. She called at 7:45, furious. Where are you? The kids are going to be late. I reminded her about the email. She'd forgotten to send it. Without it, I legally couldn't come and now I was out of time. Even if she sent it that second, I couldn't make the full trip and still get to work. She had to drive them herself. She ended up being very late to work that day. Her boss wasn't happy after that. She wanted to grant me blanket permission to come and go as needed, just cart launch access. My lawyer shut that down immediately. Follow the order every single time. The real payoff came three weeks later. She forgot to email again. This time I was supposed to pick up the kids for school. Same routine. I waited at my place. No email. I texted her a.

When I won the lottery, I went home and let my husband call me pathetic one last time. We were standing in our kitchen after I had asked him for $20 to buy groceries. $20. He actually laughed in my face while pulling out his wallet to show me the stack of money inside. You're like a homeless person begging for change, except at least they work for their money by standing outside all day. He pulled out a five dollar Bill and threw it on the floor. There's your grocery money. You better make that stretch because that's all you're getting this week. I bent down to pick up the Bill while he filmed me with his phone. This is going to my mom so I can show her what a pathetic leech you are. He said. Maybe if you crawl for it like the dog you are, I'll give you another five. I stayed on my knees looking up at him holding his phone and his wallet full of money. Come on, just one little bark and you can feed your. So this week, he said, dangling another Bill above my head. The thing about financial abuse is that it doesn't start all at once. Seven years ago when we got married, we shared everything equally and both our names were on every account. Three years into our marriage, he got laid off from his tech job and couldn't find work for three entire years. I paid our Rent his car payment, his insurance, everything while he played video games all day and told me he was networking online. I never said a word because I loved him and that's what you do for someone you love. When he finally got a new job that paid triple what he used to, he convinced me we didn't need two incomes anymore. You've been working so hard supporting us, he said sweetly. Let me take care of you now. Within two months of me quitting, he'd removed my name from the bank accounts, which he claimed was for tax purposes. He started giving me.

Right, that I can't count birds correctly. You're right that I don't know when I'm hungry. And you're especially right when you said last week that we're not compatible. He stops mid argument with Tom and goes wait, what? I never said that. I pulled out my phone and read from my notes. Tuesday eight forty seven PM you said we're not compatible because I don't appreciate intellectual discourse. Wednesday two fifteen PM you said we're not compatible because I'm too sensitive. Thursday six thirty PM you said we're not compatible because I don't challenge you mentally. Should I keep going? The whole party was silent, and Jake starts doing what he always does, arguing that those comments were taken out of context and he didn't mean it like that. I said, oh, so now you want to argue about your own words? Cool. Let me read the other 70 corrections you made this week. No. 1 Monday morning, you said my coffee order was wrong and I should get Americano instead. No. 2 Monday afternoon, you explain that my favorite color isn't actually purple, it's lavender. Number three tries to interrupt, saying this is ridiculous and embarrassing. I said, what's embarrassing is dating someone who thinks his girlfriend is wrong about literally everything, including her own favorite color. You know what you're right about, though? We're not compatible, I'm breaking up with you. He immediately starts arguing that I can't break up with him at his friend's party, and That's not how relationships work, and we need to discuss this. I said, oh, now you want to discuss something instead of just telling me I'm wrong? Too late. But don't worry. I'm sure you'll find someone else to correct. Maybe someone who doesn't know what color they like or when they're hungry or how many birds they saw. Good luck with that. Tom actually started clapping and goes, finally, someone shut him up. He does this to everyone. Jake tried to follow me out, still arguing about why I was overreacting and making a mistake. I said, you're right. It was a mistake dating. You see? I can admit when I'm wrong. Can you?

I paid my sister's rent, cleared her debt and even let her borrow my car. But when she crashed it, she called the cops on me. My parents backed her up, so I gave them a gift they'll never forget. My sister Jessica is 26 but acts 16. For years, I've been her ATM, rent, credit cards, insurance. Mom always said she was a free spirit who just needed time. Dad just avoided her. So guess who fixed her? Messes? Me. It started with a text. Took your car for the weekend. You weren't using it anyway, right? My car. The one I worked overtime for, the one with monthly payments. I called immediately. What do you mean you took my car? She sighed like I was the problem. Relax, Mike, it's just for the weekend. I should have gone to my parents, but I knew their response. It's just a car. She's your sister. Stop being selfish. So I let it go. The 2:00am call came 48 hours later. Mike, I got into an accident. My stomach dropped. Are you okay? I think so, but the car is totaled. The cops are being unfair. Just tell them it's fine. Okay? I took a slow breath. No silence. Then screaming. Are you serious? After everything I've done for you, what she'd done was drain me for years. Rent, debt, car, everything. You stole my car, Jess. You crashed it. Now you want me to lie to the police? It's just Money, Michael, you can afford it. Call mom and dad. Maybe they'll take responsibility. I'm done. I hung up. The next morning, my phone exploded. Mom, your sister could have died. Dad, we raised you better than this. I ignored them all until dad showed up at my apartment. Get dressed. We're going to the hospital. No, we're not. His face went red. She's family. You don't turn your back on family. Funny how that only applies when I'm giving in. Jessica, either you help or you're out of this family. I actually laughed. Dad, I was never in it. I was just the emergency cash fund. I shut the door in his face. Two days later, the knock I wasn't expecting. 7:00am, banging at my door, two police officers. Michael Carter. My blood turned to ice. Your sister, Jessica, is claiming you stole her car, crashed it and abandoned her at the scene. My voice went sharp. My car, the one in my name that she took without asking. Do you have proof of ownership? Of course I did. But that wasn't the problem.

An allowance and made me submit receipts for every purchase I made. He started calling me a gold digger if I bought anything for myself, even necessities. But that morning I had found $2 hidden in my coat pocket and bought a scratch off ticket at the gas station just to feel like I had some control over something. When I scratched off that ticket in my car and saw I'd won $5 million, I sat there for an hour just staring at it and planning my next move. Get up off the floor. You're embarrassing herself, he said, kicking the five dollar Bill toward me. Actually, you know what? I changed my mind about giving you any money at all. He picked up the Bill and ripped it in half, then in quarters, then threw the pieces at my face. There's your dinner. Enjoy eating paper. He walked to the refrigerator and pulled out the steak he brought home for himself last night. Watch this, he said, taking a huge bite in front of me. This is what people who actually contribute to society get to eat while parasites like you get nothing. I stood up and brush the torn money off my shirt. You wanna know something funny, I asked, reaching into my pocket. What's funny is that you think I'd waste my time listening to you, he said, with his mouth full of steak. No, what's funny is that this morning I won the lottery, I said, pulling Out the ticket and holding it up, his face went white before turning red. That's my money, too, because we're married, he screamed, lunging for the ticket. I stepped back toward the door. Actually, my lawyer says lottery winnings claimed during separation proceedings aren't marital property in this state. His mouth fell open. What separation proceedings? I smiled for the first time in years. The ones I filed this morning after I scratched off this ticket because I knew you'd try to take it all. He dropped to his knees, the same way he forced me to kneel moments before. Baby, please, we can work this out, he begged, actual tears forming in his eyes. I didn't mean any of those things. I said, I love you. He crawled toward me on his hands and knees. No, I said, walking out the door. You love controlling me. But that's over now. The last sound I heard was him screaming my name as I drove away.

$1.2 million. Jewelry collection at 200K each time. Kelly sat up straighter. Most assets were divided among family. Uncle got the lake house, aunt got the car, cousins got college funds. Then the lawyer cleared his throat. And now a special request with a personal note. Kelly leaned forward so hard she nearly fell out of her chair. To Kelly Aldridge, who showed such devoted care during my final months, I leave my most precious and valuable possession. Kelly gasped. People turned to look. She had this huge smile. The lawyer pulled out a small wooden box, placed it on the table. The room went silent. Kelly's hand shook as she opened it. Inside, with a single piece of paper, she unfolded it, still smiling. Then her face went white. The lawyer read aloud an optimized Bill for forty seven thousand three hundred forty 60 seven. The exact amount you charged to my credit card during your visit. I've highlighted the 1 200 dollar handbag you bought the day you told me you'd pray for my recovery. Consider this Bill my most precious possession because it bought me clarity about your character. The room erupted. My aunt actually laughed. The lawyer continued, to my real granddaughter, who visited me every week for 20 years, who never asked for a single dollar, I leave everything else. Approximately $2.3 million in total assets. He looked at me. I couldn't breathe. Kelly started screaming that it wasn't fair, that she deserved something for her efforts. Dad, sitting in quietly, asked to see her phone. What? Why? Kelly touched her. First your phone, now he took it. The texts were right there. Old bat is loaded. Gonna get paid playing the long game. Betting I get at least 500 K L M A O. There was even one from funeral day. Gotta play sad for a few more hours. Then I'm rich. Dad looked at Kelly like he'd never seen her before. Get out, he said. That was three days ago. Dad filed for divorce yesterday. Turns out Kelly had been stealing from him, too. Kelly and her mom moved out this morning. As they loaded boxes, Kelly looked at me with pure hatred. You poisoned her against me. I smiled. No, you did that yourself. Grandma just made sure everyone else could see it. The Bill is being sent to collections.

My gold digger stepsister threw a temper tantrum at the reading of my grandmother's will and immediately after got embarrassed in front of everyone. My stepsister Kelly is the definition of entitled. After dad married her mom three years ago, she tried banning mentions of my late mother in our house. She'd scream if I so much as said mom's name. The whole family saw through her immediately except Dad. Kelly's obsessed with and some jewelry. On her first birthday with us, dad bought her a beautiful diamond ring, cost him $3,000. She took one look at it and locked herself in her room crying all day. Later heard her on the phone. I'm telling a friend it didn't even hit my figures. But the real issue was her relationship with grandma. They openly despised each other. At Christmas Two years ago, Kelly got drunk and called grandma a bitch in front of everyone because she gave her a 50 dollar gift card instead of jewelry. I tried telling dad that Kelly was using him for money. He called me jealous and disrespectful, said I needed to give my new sister a chance. Then everything changed. Six months ago, grandma got diagnosed with terminal pancreatic cancer. Doctor said maybe half a year to live. The whole family was devastated except Kelly saw an opportunity. Literally overnight, she transformed into the world's most devoted granddaughter. Started calling grandma every morning at 8:00am sharp. She'd show up with medicine, chocolate, fancy organic Smoothies even offered to move in as her full time caretaker for free. At first I thought maybe she changed. Then I visited grandma one afternoon and found her laughing while looking at credit card statements. Your stepsister thinks I'm senile, grandma said, showing me the charges. Every visit, Kelly had been taking Grandma's wallet and charging hundreds of dollars. Designer handbags, jewelry, free spa treatments, always right after her caring granddaughter visits. Why don't you stop her, I asked. Grandma smiled. Because I'm keeping receipts. Let her dig her own grave. The months passed, Kelly kept up her act flawlessly. She'd cry at family dinners about how unfair it was that grandma was sick. Dad ate it up completely. See, Kelly really has grown. You should be more like her. I already visited grandma twice a week, had been for 20 years. But sure, Dad. Grandma passed away two weeks ago. Kelly wore all black at the funeral and cried dramatically through the whole service. It was Oscar worthy. Then came the will reading. Yesterday, the whole family gathered at the lawyer's office. Kelly sat front row next to dad. I could see dollar signs in her eyes. The lawyer started reading the Lakehouse worth 8 hundred k investment accounts totaling.

At the class reunion, my former bully asked, what do you do now? When I told him he had to go refill his drink. The moment I walked into the reunion, I saw him. Jeffrey. Standing in the center of the room like he owned the place. Laughing loud. Varsity jacket draped over his chair like some kind of trophy. The same guy who made my life absolute hell for four years. He called me a pathetic loser who'd never amount to anything. He tripped me in the hallways. He turned half the school against me just because he could. I spent lunch periods hiding in the library because being around him was unbearable. But I'm different now. I've completely transformed my life. Better job, better life, better everything. Meanwhile, Jeffrey looks exactly the same. Still loud and still cocky. Still thinks he's the king. He spotted me across the room, and I watched that familiar smirk spread across his face. He walked over, looked me up and down, and hit me with it. So, what do you do now, twerp? I could tell exactly what he was thinking. He expected to feel superior, just like old times. But I kept it vague. I work in operations management. That was all I gave him. But Jeffrey, he couldn't wait to tell me about himself. voice_to_text: A woman plants a strange seed in the ground. The next second, a human hand suddenly grows out of the soil. Curious, she brushes the dirt away. To her shock, the seed has grown into a little girl, a girl with a tiny sprout on her head who seems oddly familiar with the house. Startled, Anna asks who she is. The girl says something unbelievable. He claims to be Anna's mother. She says she grew from the earth because Anna was the one who planted the seed. Anna doesn't believe her. Her mom passed away when she was just 6 years old. But the girl doesn't argue. Instead, she heads to the kitchen to cook for Anna. She wants Anna to feel what a mother's love tastes like. She starts preparing dinner with practiced hands, but while chopping vegetables, she accidentally cuts her finger. Anna rushes over only to find green liquid dripping from the wound like sap from a plant. Soon, the meal is ready. Anna takes a cautious bite. She can't believe it, but this familiar flavor, this warmth, could only come from her mother. Her guard begins to drop. Just then, the girl tucks her hair behind her ear and a puff of dust falls from her hair. She heads to the bathroom for a shower. Moments later, while she's in the shower, Anna hears her scream. She hurries in, only to find that the girl has grown, now standing in front of her as a young Woman, she explains, as she's a plant. Water naturally makes her grow. Back in the bedroom, Anna gives her some clothes to wear. But then her phone buzzes. It's a message from her boyfriend, a proposal. Her mother sees it and immediately wants to know more. That's when she learns Anna and her boyfriend have been together for six years. They've always been deeply in love. He proposed last night. But when Anna saw the ring, she didn't feel joy. Instead of joy, she felt a strange heaviness, a weight she couldn't explain, and she turned him down. On her way home that night, she passed a flower shop selling a seed called happiness. They claimed that if you planted it, your own happiness would grow. Hoping for a little luck, Anna bought the seed. She wasn't sure if marrying him would really make her happy, but she never expected the seed to grow into her mother. Still unsure, Anna chose not to sleep in the same room that night. Her mother quietly lay alone, feeling the distance between them. Looking at the sprout on her head, she couldn't help but feel a little hurt. The next morning, Anna goes to work. To her surprise, her mother shows up at the office and just then her boyfriend arrives. Too. Worried he'll discover the truth, Anna quickly lies and says this is her cousin, then hurries her mother away. But her mother says he seems like a wonderful man. If Anna Loves him. She should accept his proposal. She just wants her daughter to be happy. Seeing Anna hesitate, her mother begins to tell a story. Twenty years ago, on Anna's sixth birthday, her mother had prepared a special gift, but Anna didn't like it. She, she had been hoping for a magic ring from her favorite cartoon. Her mother explained that the ring was sold out everywhere. She had searched five different stores but couldn't find it. Anna, always thoughtful, said it was okay. She told her mom she liked the gift anyway, though her eyes said otherwise. Then she quietly sat on the couch, eyes filled with disappointment. Her mother's heart ached. He knelt beside Anna and said, if you don't like it, don't pretend. If something really matters to you, go for it. Even if it's hard, even if it hurts, don't hide your heart. That moment stayed with Anna. She admitted she really did want that magic ring. Her mother smiled and said she'd go find one right away. She walked out the door to search again, but never made it home. There was a car accident and just like that, she was gone. Ever since, Anna has carried the guilt, clutching the ring her mother left behind, afraid to ever ask for too much again. That's why when her boyfriend proposed, she hesitated, because that ring brought back all the pain. Later that evening, her mother began searching through old boxes. She was looking for that Magic ring. But instead, she uncovered a shocking secret. What did she find? It'll change everything. Follow me to find out in the next part.

voice_to_text: This girl applied a drop of eye drops to her eye. She never expected that the moment she did, everyone would turn to look at her. At first, she thought there was something on her face. She. She quickly pulled out her phone and checked the camera. But then she noticed. Even the students sitting behind her were staring straight at her. Their expressions were blank, eerily still. They didn't even blink. The silence in the room grew heavier. An unsettling feeling crept over her. Panicked, she rushed out of the classroom. But the moment she stepped into the hallway, it happened again. Every student she passed turned their eyes to her. No matter where she went, people's eyes followed her unblinking. She couldn't understand why. Freaked out, she ran home. But just as she turned on the TV, something even stranger happened. Even the actors on the screen seemed to be staring at her. That was the last straw. She shut the TV off immediately. The next day, she went back to school as usual. But while walking through the hallway, she accidentally bumped into a boy. Her bottle of eye drops slipped out of her bag. The boy, being kind, quickly picked it up and handed it back to her. As she walked away, something clicked in her mind. That boy. He hadn't looked at her like everyone else did. After school, she found him and asked, why aren't you staring at me like everyone else? The boy Boy pulled something out of his pocket. It was a bottle of eye drops identical to hers. Then he explained. This is a special kind of eye drop. Once you use it, it tricks your mind into thinking everyone is looking at you. But in reality, no one actually is. The only people who aren't affected are those who have also used it. He had used the same eye drops before. That's why he could look away. But the truth was, everyone had been looking in their usual directions all along. It. It was all just an illusion. The effect would eventually wear off, and when it did, everything would return to normal. Hearing this, the girl finally let out a sigh of relief. But then curiosity got the best of her. Why would someone even invent something like this? She asked. The boy gave her a patient smile. Because some people have felt invisible their whole lives. People who have never been noticed, never been seen. They long for attention. Even if it's just an illusion, even if it's fake. For a moment, they can feel like they matter. His words hit her harder than she expected. She had always wanted someone's attention, too. Not just anyone's. Her mother's. After thinking it over, she did it. She put another drop in her eye. She just wanted to see her mother look at her. Just once. And the moment she did, her mother really did look at her. Her heart. Was overwhelmed with emotion. She knew it wasn't real. She knew it was just an illusion. But still, for the first time, she felt what it was like to be truly seen by someone she cared about. And it made her happy. After that day, she started using the eye drops more and more. She got used to the feeling of being noticed. voice_to_text: In Japan, there's a rare and unusual job. Sleep in a house for one night, and you can earn $100,000. Sounds like easy money, right? But almost no one wants to do it. The job? A ghost cleaner. They move into homes where someone has recently died. If they stay there for a full week, the place is considered cleansed. Then the landlord can sell or rent it out like any regular property. Anna is a professional ghost cleaner. She owns a spirit lamp in the house, and if it starts flickering, that means a ghost is nearby. One night, the lamp began to flicker. Anna started searching the rooms. She opened the bathroom door, and sure enough, there was a ghost. A man. He stared right at Anna, surprised she could see him. That's because Anna has a rare gift. She. She can see spirits. The ghost tried to scare her, but Anna didn't flinch. She calmly shut the door. Then, right in front of the ghost, she started getting ready for bed. The ghost tried harder to scare her, but she didn't even blink. Why? Because she knew something important. Ghosts can't touch anything. Not objects, not people. The next morning, Anna started drawing. She sketched the ghost's face, capturing both the spooky and silly side. It's her habit. She's loved drawing since she was a kid. And ever since becoming a ghost cleaner, she's been documenting every spirit she needs. The ghost was curious. Why would a Girl like her choose this job. So Anna told him her story. When she was five, her mom dropped her off at her grandmother's house, saying she'd come back soon. But she never did. Anna grew up believing her mom had abandoned her. She became quiet, withdrawn, and had no friends. Then. Then, just after turning 18, her beloved grandmother passed away. With nowhere to go, she ended up living with her shady uncle. He's the one who made her a ghost cleaner. Hearing all this, the ghost felt something he hadn't felt in years. Sympathy. The two spent a few quiet days together. But one night, Anna found a box of music tapes under her bed. When the ghost saw them, he lit up with excitement. Turns out he used to be a musician. But no matter how long he worked, his music was never recognized. Eventually, it broke him, and he died in that very room. That tape. It was his final recording, his favorite piece. He begged Anna for a favor. He wanted her to deliver the tape to a music company. Then he could finally rest in peace and be reborn. Anna agreed. And just like he promised, the ghost disappeared. Her job there was done. She was about to play his music when suddenly her phone rang. It was her uncle. He had lined up a new job, which meant Anna had to move again to another haunted house. But nothing could have prepared her For the ghost she was about to meet next. Want to hear what happens after that? Follow me and leave a comment. I'll be sharing the rest of the story soon.

Como era de esperar, cuando Ana se dio la vuelta, el espíritu había quedado fuera del santuario. En ese momento, Ana había adquirido la habilidad de ver espíritus. Efectivamente, unos días después el director trajo buenas noticias, la profesora había dado a luz a un bebé sano y a salvo debido a que la profesora estaba de baja por maternidad. Todas las chicas estaban llenas de curiosidad por este atractivo nuevo profesor y solo Ana Lucía nerviosa ya que vio a un fantasma negro asentado detrás del nuevo profesor. Durante la clase, el profesor hizo pasar lista y llamó a Jenny y las demás chicas de la clase comenzaron a murmurarlo con un poco de celos, incitándole a que también recordara Sus nombres. Sin embargo, en ese momento, Ana notó que la sombra negra estaba mirando fijamente a Jenny, como si también estuviera influenciada por los celos.
